At present, the only option available in a Bhutanese divorce is for each of the separated partners to claim half of the couples property and income. Reparations for hurt and humiliation cannot be claimed. This means that Chinese women who marry Bhutanese men may not be able to gain control of certain assets in a Chinese divorce.

Medical and childcare costs are another major consideration in divorce. If a wife sues her husband financially, most courts in Bhutan will force him to provide half of the medical expenses she and her children incur. Other forms of marital responsibility, including expenses associated with caring for children, are rarely included in a Bhutan divorce.

Marital breakdowns are relatively uncommon in Bhutan. The most common reasons for divorce are adultery, alcoholism and discord between the spouses. Another reason for marital disruption not commonly seen in Bhutan is sexual infidelity on the part of the husband.

Marriage in Bhutan is mainly a contract between partners concerning property and inheritance rights. Divorce is considered to be a form of separation between partners, but the rights and responsibilities of each of the partners in marriage remain the same.

Many outside lawyers feel that the laws surrounding Bhutan the changing marital laws fall short of the current Bhutanese law.
